No existing scroll tests. Let me now directly fix the bug and write a test. But first, let me understand the exact fix needed.

Looking at the `OpenMenu()` method (lines 694-719), the scroll logic is at lines 707-715:

```csharp
//Scroll the active item on each opening
if (_activeItemId != null)
{
    var index = Items.FindIndex(x => x.ItemId == _activeItemId);
    if (index > 0)
    {
        var item = Items[index];
        await ScrollToItemAsync(item);
    }
}
```

And in `OnAfterRenderAsync` (lines 1441-1457):
```csharp
if (_needsHighlightAfterRender)
{
    _needsHighlightAfterRender = false;
    await InvokeAsync(async () =>
    {
        if (MultiSelection)
        {
            var firstNonDisabled = Items.FirstOrDefault(x => !x.Disabled);
            await HighlightItemAsync(firstNonDisabled);
        }
        else
        {
            await HighlightItemForValueAsync(ReadValue);
        }
    });
}
```

The fix should move the scroll logic from `OpenMenu()` to `OnAfterRenderAsync()`, or add scroll logic alongside the highlight logic in `OnAfterRenderAsync` since by that point the items are registered.

Let me now write the test and fix the code:

